T1  - Troubling news: challenging politics, perceptions and practices of newspapers contructions of teachers
AN  - 1719242618
AB  - Newspapers are instruments of the public domain; performative texts that enable public engagement in teachers' work. However, they are not neutral. They construct public opinion through specific portrayals of teachers that in turn work to construct particular knowledge. Through a discursive analysis of texts from The Australian newspaper and interviews with teachers and journalists, I provided insights into the politics and practices of what Foucault describes as 'regimes of truth' that circulate in the media about teachers' work. My study identified four media constructs of teachers: the regulated accountable teacher, the transparent audited teacher, the failing incompetent teacher and the privileged reckless teacher. These constructs identified in my findings were generally critical, negative, oppressive and reductionist regarding teachers and their work. I problematise such discourses as dangerous and potentially destructive as they erode public trust for teachers and the teaching profession. My analysis of the media constructions of teachers contributes to the sociology of education by enabling understandings of media practices and advocates for researchers and educators to actively participate in the media process and trouble the news, rather than being bystanders who are frustrated and annoyed with the troubling news they read in the press.
